column4: (+); "they make small shallow holes at the distance of about 5" from each other"
compost [underlined]; plant in wooded area in order that leaves from trees will have replenished soil
"field work falls to the men while the women are kept busy inside the village"
irrigation of rice fields due to Indian influence
land belongs to clan or village - if cultivator dies without heirs, use can be obtained through permission of chief
with the priest's assistance farmer fixes on lucky day for sowing his crops
They raise horses but do not hide them - introduced from India
the sopo - used as a meeting house for the village council as well as the place that houses Batak ceremonial objects
kubur - coffins placed in fenced enclosure
Double-fence of wooden planks 9’ high with hedge of prickly bamboo in front
sopo has a loft used as a storeroom
cultivator’s heirs have rights to cultivate the same property – “right of possession only can be gained by cultivator”
“interest reckoned at one hundred percent” in order to pay off debts of commoners
(+); inferred in order to start cycle of pawnship
benzoin camphor & cassia of inlands exchanged for iron, steel brass wire & salt of the coast
agreements over loans. Enforceable only to the extent that wars between village result over failure to pay back
Labor mobilized by compensation in form of working in return for work done
Members of the community required to work radja's land
smiths have a distinct & recognized position; tools are inherited from father to son
no direct taxation – subjects required to work radja’s land
maintaining order in markets [underlined]; chief and guard are present in order to preserve order
priests invokes blessings for people from their ancestors up to 7 generations
bride price completely paid groom demands clothing & jewlery for his wife
society divided into groups of nobles, commoners & slaves
only members of nobility allowed to have more than 1 wive & slavery
only nobles allowed slaves & more than 1 wife
members of the ruling marga or clan – under leadership of radja – own land of community
members of the nobility – the radja’s relatives - permitted more than 1 wife and slaves
bodies of commoners placed on plattforms
Slaves – 2 groups: house slaves & field slaves
Radjas & family were the only slave owners & the only traders
system resembles feudalism, village heads often belong to same family
command military service [underlined]; those who refuse to fight banished & property confiscations
radja acts as judge in council
radja chosen from among members of an eligible family – clan
areas loosely divided into lesser units with own village heads
radjas entitled to labor of their subjects to work land & build houses
radjas of the Toba are preserved with salt & camphor & placed in wooden chests
in warfare guilty party paid fine & held feast of conciliation & then swore an oath
walking over molten iron, hand in boiling water, ducking in water, for debtor in case of war
council of villagers headed by radja
(-); disputes between village settled through arbitration of 2 neutral radjas
“adat” – traditional laws to which all decisions of the council must conform
“chiefs also receive a portion of the fines levied”
refusal to take part in warfare punished by confiscation of property
stocks [underlined] - mentioned as punishment for runaway slaves
those unable to pay fines made slaves or those who had committed murder
as a result of debts, boundary dispute, insult to radja
village warned with a “pula” – piece of bamboo bearing a letter placed in area of village to be attacked
those who refused subject to loss of property & banishment
chiefs carry war banners when raiding
(+); spies mentioned as punished by being eaten
captives brought back kept in compound & eaten when adversaries committed any “atrocity”.
captives kept too as hostages to force opponents to surrender
if Batak kills enemy given reward
penalty for failding to take part in warfare is confiscation of property
neutral chiefs arbitrate, fine payed & feast & oath
in Toba inhabitants killed or taken prisoner
one who has lived a good life borne by wind to heaven – one who has lived in evil to cauldron
blood of young hog sprinkled on coffin
